00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:19.820
So let's talk a little
bit about the things

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:22.430
that we saw in those videos.

00:08:22.430 --> 00:08:24.720
and how they apply
to battlecode.

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:27.160
So there's a whole
question of centralized

00:08:27.160 --> 00:08:28.800
versus decentralized control.

00:08:28.800 --> 00:08:31.086
And in the ones that we saw,
they weren't centralized.

00:08:31.086 --> 00:08:32.460
So I'm going to
show you examples

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:34.980
in battlecode of both of those.

00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:38.299
Now, those can have
impacts on whether there's

00:08:38.299 --> 00:08:41.620
a radio attack possible,
whether your strategy's going

00:08:41.620 --> 00:08:43.990
to be vulnerable to that.

00:08:43.990 --> 00:08:46.880
Whether it's like a
map dependent strategy,

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:50.030
because maybe on a
centralized controller,

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:51.940
it works really well
if it's a tiny map.

00:08:51.940 --> 00:08:53.440
But maybe if it's
a huge map, you've

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:56.060
got to start having multiple
swarms that are independent.

00:08:56.060 --> 00:09:00.060
And talking about
distributing information

00:09:00.060 --> 00:09:03.380
is another thing
to worry about it.

00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:07.110
So let's consider that
in the boyds model, which

00:09:07.110 --> 00:09:10.520
is supposed to sound like birds
if you have a Brooklyn accent,

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:15.460
they considered several aspects
for computing the next position

00:09:15.460 --> 00:09:18.550
for each actor in the swarm.

00:09:18.550 --> 00:09:22.110
The separation of each
one to its neighbors.

00:09:22.110 --> 00:09:25.750
The pushing together of each
one, which they call cohesion,

00:09:25.750 --> 00:09:27.720
because the smarter
you sound, the more

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:31.430
Ph.D. Money and grant
money you can make.

00:09:31.430 --> 00:09:34.367
They talk about alignment
so that everybody's

00:09:34.367 --> 00:09:35.450
facing the same direction.

00:09:35.450 --> 00:09:37.180
Now, that's somewhat
different this year

00:09:37.180 --> 00:09:39.780
than it has been in
past battlecode years.

00:09:39.780 --> 00:09:43.220
And then I guess they don't
talk too much about it,

00:09:43.220 --> 00:09:49.090
but they considered the later
effects of group splitting

00:09:49.090 --> 00:09:53.100
and lane creation,
which we saw today.

00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:54.930
So let's see here.

00:09:54.930 --> 00:09:57.420
I showed some examples
of these things.

00:09:57.420 --> 00:09:59.660
Alignment this year
is worth noting

00:09:59.660 --> 00:10:05.450
that there used to be a method
where you could take the robot

00:10:05.450 --> 00:10:07.210
info and do dot direction.

00:10:07.210 --> 00:10:10.650
You could get the direction
of any robot that you can see.

00:10:10.650 --> 00:10:13.140
Now, in this year's battlecode,
there's no direction.

00:10:13.140 --> 00:10:14.640
So what are you going to do?

00:10:14.640 --> 00:10:16.350
So let's see here.

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:18.760
You can get the distances
for separation and cohesion.

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:20.520
I mean, these are
just a fancy way

00:10:20.520 --> 00:10:23.200
of just saying there's
like a spring between you

00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:23.870
and the others.

00:10:23.870 --> 00:10:28.130
And this one is just saying that
you're headed the right way.

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:30.446
There's really almost
nothing complicated to it.

00:10:30.446 --> 00:10:32.820
And we're going to end up
seeing some pretty neat looking

00:10:32.820 --> 00:10:35.780
behavior from very simple rules.

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:37.900
So yeah, let's talk
about how you're

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:40.570
going to know that you're
facing the right direction.

00:10:40.570 --> 00:10:42.690
I mean, you could check
all the neighbors.

00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:46.210
Let's see here, face
the right direction.

00:10:46.210 --> 00:10:48.690
You could check
all the neighbors

00:10:48.690 --> 00:10:50.700
against all the other ones.

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:54.120
So you'd be checking
to see if robot

00:10:54.120 --> 00:10:57.150
ID number 97 was from this
position, and then that one.

00:10:57.150 --> 00:10:59.290
And then you would try
to find where he was,

00:10:59.290 --> 00:11:01.210
and correlate that,
and get the direction.

00:11:01.210 --> 00:11:03.910
And then take an average for
all the robots that you can see.

00:11:03.910 --> 00:11:06.140
That would be really
computationally expensive.

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:08.410
Another option is
to say, all right,

00:11:08.410 --> 00:11:12.950
take average of
all allied robots.

00:11:12.950 --> 00:11:16.500
Or all within a range.

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:20.700
And then see how
that average moves.

00:11:20.700 --> 00:11:22.280
So that's like an
implicit direction

00:11:22.280 --> 00:11:25.520
for the group of allied robots.

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:28.500
And then an individual
robot, by doing that,

00:11:28.500 --> 00:11:30.030
could see where all of them are.

00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:32.430
Another option is just
to radio broadcast

00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:35.720
so that somebody somewhere is
deciding what direction to go.

00:11:35.720 --> 00:11:38.650
Or maybe all of them vote on the
direction that they want to go,

00:11:38.650 --> 00:11:40.608
because maybe some of
them are close to enemies

00:11:40.608 --> 00:11:42.260
