to the target location,

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:22.090
which is like the waypoint.

00:33:22.090 --> 00:33:24.370
And now I'm going to
apply a target weight,

00:33:24.370 --> 00:33:26.980
because maybe I really want
to get there if I'm far away.

00:33:26.980 --> 00:33:29.530
But if I'm kind of close,
I don't really care.

00:33:29.530 --> 00:33:31.835
So now I have this function
called target weight, where

00:33:31.835 --> 00:33:34.230
if my distance squared
is greater than 100,

00:33:34.230 --> 00:33:35.352
I'll call the weighting 5.

00:33:35.352 --> 00:33:37.060
If my distance squared
is greater than 9,

00:33:37.060 --> 00:33:38.250
I'll call the weighting 2.

00:33:38.250 --> 00:33:41.520
And if I'm really close, then
I'll call the weighting 1.

00:33:41.520 --> 00:33:44.580
So that's sort of giving me
this spring-like behavior

00:33:44.580 --> 00:33:46.240
